Neuchatel, particularly with the advent of spring, has consistently been one of the most delightful, delicate, sprightly

529 GERMAN MAY WINE (Gebrueder Lob) . . . . . 1.79 1.29 14.50

One of the most provocative aromas in the garden during the spring is one which few people associate with drinking. They inhale the fresh, tingling aroma of the woodruff plant, but never quite associate it with the bouquet of “May Wine.” This one has just reached us from the Rhine — we opened a bottle and were intrigued by the garden-fresh tang which greeted us, the smell of woodruff. We happily inform you that it costs but $1.29 —a delightful and inexpensive wine to serve chilled as an aperitif during the coming warm days.

WURZBURGER LINDLINSBERG 1953 Estate Bottled, the Julius Spital . . . . . . 2.49 1.99 22.65

Wurzburg, an important city of Franconia, is quite as famous for its wine as for its beer. Its wines are bottled in the attractive, squat green flagons called Bocksbeutel, generally known as Steinwein. The best wine of the area is estate bottled by the Julius Spital, a celebrated charity hospital in the heart of the historic city of Wurzburg. As far as we can judge, this marks the first time that this supreme example of Franconian wine has been made available to the New York public. We suggest you try a bottle or two at this low cost.

ALSATIAN RIESLING 1952 (Caves Hanhart) . — Value Continued 1.29 14.50

Riesling is one of the two greatest of all white wine grapes and particularly thrives among the steep hills of Alsace,

where it produces a dry wine of unusual charm. Here is an excellent example at a price that will permit serving freely this summer.

GEWURZTRAMINER 1952 (Caves Hanhart) . . Value Continued 1.49 16.95

The most highly regarded grape of the district is the Gewurztraminer which yields a wine not quite as dry as the

Riesling, but with a bouquet that is more prominent and more highly perfumed. This wine would be an excep- tional value at $2.00.
